<P> <P><b><i>
<font face="Georgia" size="4" color="#9F3215">
Milo Says:
</font></i></b><BR>


   I figure I'd better try to get to the bottom of this while
I'm still able.<P>

   I'm glad that you wrote to me; your response offers me a
good context in which to define the reasoning behind my
response to your daughter.  My "personal comments" about
her possibly having an agenda or being dissatisfied with her
own appearance were based on the magnitude of error of
her observation.  Of the seven races of human-shaped
women in the game, only four of them come provocatively
dressed, so I naturally detected peripheral issues on Stacy's
part.<P>

   I suppose this has become a no-win debate for me, now --
mother-daughter attack teams tend to be pretty high on the
commercial scale of unassailability.  Nevertheless, I will say
that I can see how a pre-existing aversion to revealing
clothing on beautiful women would cause someone to take
notice of the half-elves, dark elves, woodland elves, and
barbarians, while ignoring the humans, high elves, and
erudites.  If my suspicions are off target, then this is a
chance for me and anyone who shares them to acquire
insight into a position that has us perplexed. I eagerly await
your happily-offered reply.<P>

   As for my playing a gnomish female, I find them and the
female halflings rather adorable, in much the same way a
father typically adores his little girl.  That's why I play those
characters; how this makes me less manly is something else
that I don't understand.<P>


<HR align="center" width="85%"><P>

 What's your IQ?<P>
 
 -sidis

