				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				Ok, Sad as i am to se the demise od said colume, I think that u lot shood realy fank Milo for makin you fink twice aboot wot you type.<BR>
<BR>
Does you wealyu fink dat typin wot you sais iz a good fing. if i did dat i wod not ave da kool high paying job wot i az got now.<BR>
<BR>
Wen i did my letta for da job i wrote it az i fought is shud ave bin written. wiv da proppa gramma an da stuff. not az i duz speek. n i got da job. If i ad dun it az i saiz da wudz den i would not ave.<BR>
<BR>
Wud you pay a bloke wat writs a letta like dis a job?<BR>
<BR>
Translaton.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Sad as I am to se the demise of the ask Milo column, I think that people should really thank Milo for making them think twice about the way they prepare a written document.<BR>
<BR>
Do you really think that writing a letter in the same manner as your speech is a good thing? If I had that I would not have the high paying job that I have now.<BR>
<BR>
When i did my letter for the job I wrote it in the manner I expected the employer to accept. Not as I would have &#8220;spoken&#8221; thus ensuring at the very least an interview.<BR>
<BR>
After a lengthy interview, during which the prospective employer had ample time to ascertain the level my abilities within the prescribed areas I was offered the position.<BR>
<BR>
Do you really think that said employer would have even interviewed me given a letter written in the style above?<BR>
<BR>
Whilst I do not claim to have an exceptional ability with the written language, I do pride myself on the fact that given sufficient time I can produce a comprehendible and well-written letter, email or report.<BR>
<BR>
Having said that when In a &#8220;chat&#8221; type situation yes, I will use terms such as &#8220;U&#8221; and so on.<BR>

